Many metabolic pathways involve multi-step reactions. Consider the following pathway, where E represents different enzymes, and A, B, C, D and F represent substrates and products of the pathway.

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \begin{array}{llll}
\mathrm{E}_{1} & \mathrm{E}_{2} & \mathrm{E}_{3} & \mathrm{E}_{4}
\end{array} \\
& \mathrm{~A} \rightarrow \mathrm{B} \rightarrow \mathrm{C} \rightarrow \mathrm{D} \rightarrow \mathrm{F}
\end{aligned}
$$

In the example above, assume that $D$ is an allosteric inhibitor of the enzyme $\mathrm{E}_{2}$. D would
A: Compete with $\mathrm{B}$ for binding to the $\mathrm{E}_{2}$ active site
B: Compete with $\mathrm{F}$ for binding with $\mathrm{E}_{2}$
C: Bind directly to the substrate $\mathrm{B}$ and prevent it from entering the $\mathrm{E}_{2}$ active site
D: Bind $\mathrm{E}_{2}$ at a site different from the active site but change the shape of the active site so $\mathrm{B}$ can no longer bind
E: Bind $\mathrm{E}_{2}$ at the active site, change its shape and prevent $\mathrm{B}$ from binding the active site

Many metabolic pathways involve multi-step reactions. Consider the following pathway, where E represents different enzymes, and A, B, C, D and F represent substrates and products of the pathway.

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \begin{array}{llll}
\mathrm{E}_{1} & \mathrm{E}_{2} & \mathrm{E}_{3} & \mathrm{E}_{4}
\end{array} \\
& \mathrm{~A} \rightarrow \mathrm{B} \rightarrow \mathrm{C} \rightarrow \mathrm{D} \rightarrow \mathrm{F}
\end{aligned}
$$

Feedback inhibition of this pathway may involve
A: The product of the final reaction, $\mathrm{F}$, interacting with and inhibiting $\mathrm{E}_{1}$
B: F interacting with and inhibiting product $B$
C: Product $\mathrm{B}$ interacting with and inhibiting $\mathrm{E}_{4}$
D: Product $\mathrm{C}$ interacting with and inhibiting $\mathrm{E}_{4}$
E: $\mathrm{E}_{3}$ interacting with and inhibiting $\mathrm{E}_{2}$
